          "lines": [
            0,
            60,
            123,
            186,
            251
          ],
          "text": "Checking nets on the PCB is quite slow. Worse, checking the extents of a single net can be quite slow. Right now, on every mouse move, the system calculates in the gui thread the extent of the hovered net. I want to do better, because this can easily take a full second.",
          "uuid": "28ec7bb2",
          "cc": [
            { "typ": "markup",
              "cre": "2026-06-06T19:35:25.937",
              "mod": "2026-06-06T19:35:25.937",
              "end": 174,
              "start": 157,
              "style": 1,
              "uuid": "bf241626"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    { "typ": "textblock",
      "cre": "2026-06-06T20:56:39.648",
      "mod": "2026-06-06T21:13:25.284",
      "h": 212.494,
      "ind": 1,
      "sheet": 0,
      "split": [ ],
      "uuid": "e435e6ae",
      "y0": 191.83,
      "cc": [
        { "typ": "text",
          "cre": "2026-06-06T20:56:39.648",
          "mod": "2026-06-06T21:13:25.284",
          "lines": [
            0,
            59,
            118,
            180,
            248,
            312,
            369,
            432,
            484
          ],
          "text": "I have several thoughts, but no immediate solution. First, why does this take so long? The basic answer is that every object that gets added to the net triggers a loop through all objects to see if it touches it. So, for N objects in the schematic and M objects on the net, the search is O(N M). But why is that slow on a modern computer? Pressing ^C in gdb shows that there is not a single low-level function that is obviously the culprit. Consistently, we’re inside a deep stack of insertRecursively, but within that, there is just lots of variation.",
          "uuid": "b353ceff",
          "cc": [
            { "typ": "markup",
              "cre": "2026-06-06T21:02:38.277",
