          "lines": [
            0,
            60,
            123,
            183,
            242,
            307,
            369,
            428
          ],
          "text": "One way to potentially make this much faster is to begin to assign a unique integer to each object so we avoid the endless NodeID business. Then we calculate the bounding box of each object. Then we construct a matrix of potentially touching objects and a matrix of actually touching objects. Is it easy to expand that to a matrix of connected objects? Gemini suggests that for sparse matrices like ours, the depth-first-search approach is faster, and that boost can do this readily:",
          "uuid": "51a9da8d"
        }
      ]
    },
